The stock of the old publicatione iu the possession of the Society is so greatly reduced that it is by no means easy, and it will soon be impossible, to supply full sets of our works to any new members who may wish to acquire them.

In Sir Walter Calverley Trevelyan the Society has lost, it may be said, one of its founders, a, gentleman who for more than half a century has been a friend of scholare, and a sympathizer and helper in literary work throughout the North of England. There are now but four names upon our list of members which stood there at the foundation of the Society in 1834.
